<span id="freeTextContainer10258918393959671020">Very grandiose similes indeed, haha! :D As an onlooker here (I am not familiar with this author&apos;s work, this book or the content--plot, characters, et</span>
  <span id="freeText10258918393959671020" style="display:none">Very grandiose similes indeed, haha! :D As an onlooker here (I am not familiar with this author's work, this book or the content--plot, characters, etc), I think what makes these similes not work is: some of them are very lengthy with unnecessary detail--they go on too long and this dilutes the effectiveness or 'punch' that is often the reason one uses a simile in the first place, b) some come across as too jarring and 'out of place'--the one about the Seljuk Turks and lone Christian seems particularly distracting in its effect...and plus it also feels like a bit of showing off, like a subject that isn't too popularly known that the author (narrator) may have some deeper knowledge of and they are just itching to to slip it into the narrative, even though it doesn't relate to anything else going on...<br /><br />Some say that similes/metaphors are overused in writing in general ("METAPHORS. Always too many in poems. Always too many in anybody's writing." - Flaubert, Dictionary of Accepted Ideas :D), but if one is to use them, I think these ones you quoted are a good example of 'less is more'--how much more 'punch' the similes might have delivered with less words and more focus.</span>
